<paper id="1488056159"><title>Time-Stamping with Binary Linking Schemes</title><year>1998</year><authors><author org="Cybernetica" id="287036867">Ahto Buldas</author><author org="Cybernetica" id="2076234968">Peeter Laud</author><author org="Cybernetica" id="15605393">Helger Lipmaa</author><author org="Cybernetica" id="169085603">Jan Willemson</author></authors><n_citation>110</n_citation><doc_type>Patent</doc_type><references><reference>54173073</reference><reference>201259369</reference><reference>1660562555</reference><reference>1993716793</reference><reference>1997911919</reference><reference>2010939995</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0055749</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.0">Time stamping</keyword><keyword weight="0.40128">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.43848">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.40421">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.44071">Electronic document</keyword><keyword weight="0.48924">Digital signature</keyword><keyword weight="0.47456">Timestamp</keyword><keyword weight="0.42909">Hash function</keyword><keyword weight="0.38645">Binary number</keyword><keyword weight="0.62431">Cryptographic nonce</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A digital signature certification system creates a nonce and attaches a time to the nonce to create a time stamped nonce uniquely identifying the time stamp then attaches the time stamped nonce to a document, attaches a digital signature to the document, then attaches a time to the document to form a time stamped document, so that the nonce uniquely identifies the signature on the document.</abstract></paper>